reviews.title: The biggest surprise is the friendly service
reviews.text: Friendly service, great sushi and tasty desserts. Basically everything you expect from an ‘all you can eat’. The fact that the service is also good remains a pleasant surprise, because in the Dutch hospitality industry that is less and less obvious. Great address if you like this concept. If I'm in Epe again I would quietly come back here.

reviews.title: Excellent Japanese (performed by Chinese)
reviews.text: Good restaurant, great food, good variety although it could be a little more for vegans, (where is the tofu?) generally good and friendly staff, good value for money and a pleasant atmosphere. That's why we come here regularly. This restaurant I dare to recommend.

tips.body: Als grap bedoeld: Gaarne zeuren om tofu gerechten, dan krijg ik dit misschien in de toekomst op mijn bord. ;-). Goed restaurant.

reviews.title: thrifty take out
reviews.text:
It says something about the owner if on a >40 EUR bill he adds 0.10 EUR for a plastic bag (that you can't refuse to take) and 0.25 EUR transaction fee if you credit his bank account through an instant bank account transaction (IDEAL) or 1 EUR for a credit card transaction.

What bugs me is that for my order of 40 sushi's or so he gives a total of 4 small soy sauce sachets. Needless to say this wasn't enough (it should have been 10 or so) and the food therefore wasn't satisfactory. Too bad, while the soy sauce lasted it was quite good.

Berlin is nothing if not resilient, having outlasted many turbulent periods in its history. Those scars still show today in the stark distinction felt between the east and west sides of the city even though it’s been decades since the Berlin Wall came down. And for a European capital city, it’s not conventionally beautiful like Paris or London. Instead, Berlin embraces its eccentric hodgepodge of grit and glamour.
